snippet.textDisplay: Idk how it's not on the internet but... I now love DS so much because there's always a loophole. Even in this fight I got her down on my 10th try solo with the following strategy. In the arena there's the alcove... Just like in the Midir arena, we should take advantage of the small space there is behind the father. Just stay there, she'll teleport behind you and you'll see her immediately. She won't do any range attacks or crazy jumps any more inside the cage, it turns into a boxing match. I had the exile sword, dragonslayer armor and the crest shield, dark bug pills, frost ring, wolf ring. Stability is the key + some frost and dark protection. Use amber only for the third phase. Run to the alcove and wait. That's it. Roll and push. Sometimes she'll even freeze in the corner üòÖ she is beatable and it's easy and fun. Second phase is pretty easy too.

snippet.textDisplay: I absolutely hate this boss so much. Friede just swings non stop and constantly switches between fast and slow swings to confuse you, and she dodges away immedietly after she's done with her combos so you'd almost never get a chance to hit her without just blocking her attacks, forcing you to take some damage just to get a chance to hit her. Her second phase is just chaos without Gael helping you. Friede and Ariandel often never wanna seperate, which visually messes with you because Friede will often be hiding behind Ariandel if you choose to fight him. But if you choose to fight Friede, he will be constantly smashing his flaming bowl around you, which will force you to try rolling his and her attacks at the same time, and he has two identical combos where one ends with a huge AOI attack which will kill you instantly if he does it while Friede is attacking. And if they do decide to seperate, you'll only be able to see one at a time while locked on, and if you lock onto Friede, Ariandel will start doing his ranged fire attacks behind you, and if you lock onto Ariandel, Friede will attack you from behind, and you know how annoying her moveset is which makes either option terrible. Then in her third phase, she does the annoying constantly dodging away with new and even longer and more dangerous combos. She seems to dodge around even more in the third phase. Literally the only opening you get to hit her in that phase is when either she's done doing ranged ice magic and black flame attacks and is about to to her grab attack, or when you dodge her grab attack. This fight should of had a saving feature where it saves after the first phase, because doing two phases and then dying over and over is just annoying. This is the worst fight in the game, and maybe one of the worst Fromsoftware bosses made.

snippet.textDisplay: When I fought Malenia, I was reminded of Sister Friede. Both are duelists that can either be patient or overwhelmingly aggressive, but also can be staggered and punished. Although I have to say, I preferred Sister Friede just because the amount of damage she does is a lot more reasonable. That compared to how Malenia can just kill you with 2 or 3 attacks, which to me seems like a crappy punishment to add challenge. Some of Malenia's attacks are confounding in how you have to position and time your dodges. Her life steal effect I could deal with if that wasn't a problem. Malenia was just too unforgiving and unfair, even by Souls games standards. But Sister Friede gives you clear ways to understand the fight, and doesn't completely screw you over if you make a mistake since it's only her biggest attacks that will knock off most of your health.

snippet.textDisplay:
Friede's third phase is such a cool fight, her moves are a sight to behold and she's incredibly challenging yet still absolutely fair. This is what the Malenia fight in Elden Ring should've been like, but instead we got a boss that heals herself with every hit and has one move that can literally end your run if you don't know the frame perfect dodging technique that few people can master.
Sister Friede is a fun fight, Malenia isn't. When you finally  beat Friede you feel an overwhelming sense of accomplishment and pride and all you can think is "What an epic fight that was!" whereas with Malenia all you feel is relief because you somehow survived and don't have to fight her again and you're just thinking "I'm glad that's over, I never wanna fight her again."
